				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$1.55\ {\upmu }\mathrm {m}$$\end{document} were converted to visible light (λ=631nm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\lambda =631\ \mathrm {nm}$$\end{document}) with an estimated efficiency of 90% (the ratio of upconverted photons to the input in infrared photons). The setup for the wavelength conversion was later miniaturized by Langrock et al. (2005), who used a waveguide written in the PPLN crystal to achieve high conversion efficiency with a pump power of a few tens of mW. The scheme could be used to convert either photons at λ=1.32μm\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
